ute the next unique, strictly larger proposal number.\n4. isQuorum — quorum detection: given the total number of acceptors and a count of responses, decide whether a majority quorum has been reached.\n5. learnerChosenValue — learner logic: given accepted (number, value) reports, determine whether any value has been accepted by a quorum and, if so, which.\nNetworking, persistence, timeouts, and leader election remain out of scope for all of the above. This run covers exactly method (0): the proposer\'s Phase 2a value-selection rule, unchanged from the prior draft.\n\nScope note (important, please review): "Implement Paxos protocol" describes an entire distributed consensus system involving multiple roles (proposers, acceptors, learners), message passing, persistent state, and failure handling. That cannot be expressed as a single method for this pipeline. This specification covers exactly one core, self-contained rule of Paxos: the proposer\'s value-selection rule used in Phase 2a. The remaining Paxos components — acceptor promise logic (Phase 1b), acceptor accept logic (Phase 2b), learner quorum/chosen-value detection, proposal-number generation, and any networking or state persistence — are explicitly out of scope and are enumerated above as separate specification runs.\n\nPurpose and behavior: After a proposer receives promise responses from a quorum of acceptors, Paxos requires it to propose the value associated with the highest-numbered previously accepted proposal among those responses; only if no acceptor in the quorum has previously accepted any value may the proposer use its own value. This method implements that selection rule as a pure function.\n\nInputs:\n- acceptedNums: Array Nat — the proposal numbers of previously accepted proposals reported in the promise responses. Each entry corresponds positionally to the entry at the same index in acceptedVals. Only responses that actually reported a previously accepted proposal are included; responses reporting "nothing accepted yet" must be filtered out by the caller before invoking this method.\n- acceptedVals: Array Int — the values of those previously accepted proposals, positionally aligned with acceptedNums.\n- defaultVal: Int — the proposer\'s own desired value, used only when no acceptor reported a previously accepted proposal.\n\nOutput:\n- result: Int — the value the proposer must propose in Phase 2a.\n\nPreconditions (explicit):\n- acceptedNums.size = acceptedVals.size. Behavior is unspecified if the lengths differ; callers must guarantee equal lengths.\n- Proposal numbers are natural numbers; there is no upper bound.\n\nBehavior specification:\n- If both arrays are empty (no acceptor reported a prior acceptance), the result is defaultVal.\n- Otherwise, the result is acceptedVals[i] where i is an index at which acceptedNums attains its maximum value.\n- Tie-breaking assumption: in standard Paxos, distinct acceptors reporting the same proposal number must have accepted the same value (this is a protocol invariant), so ties are semantically harmless. For determinism at the specification level, we require that if the maximum proposal number occurs at multiple indices, the value at the FIRST (lowest) such index is returned. This is a recorded assumption a reviewer may change.\n\nBoundaries: The maximum is inclusive; an array of size 1 trivially selects its only value. Proposal number 0 is a legal accepted proposal number (assumption: the caller does not reserve 0 as a sentinel; reviewer may change this).\n\nMutation and ordering: The method does not mutate its inputs. Input ordering matters only for the first-occurrence tie-break; otherwise the result is order-insensitive.\n\nDeterminism: Fully deterministic — identical inputs always produce identical output.\n\nEdge and degenerate cases:\n- Empty inputs: returns defaultVal.\n- Single element: returns that element\'s value regardless of defaultVal.\n- All proposal numbers equal: returns the value at index 0.\n- defaultVal is ignored whenever the arrays are non-empty, even if defaultVal is "better" by any measure.\n\nComplexity requirement: O(n) time in the length of the arrays, O(1) additional space.\n\nWorked example: acceptedNums = [3, 7, 5], acceptedVals = [10, 20, 30], defaultVal = 0. The maximum proposal number is 7 at index 1, so the result is 20.\n\nSecond worked example: acceptedNums = [], acceptedVals = [], defaultVal = 42. No prior acceptances exist, so the result is 42.\n\n=== METHOD_SIGNATURE ===\n\nmethod chooseProposalValue(acceptedNums: Array Nat, acceptedVals: Array Int, defaultVal: Int) returns (result: Int)\n\n=== TEST_CASES ===\n\n{\n  "test_1": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [3, 7, 5], "acceptedVals": [10, 20, 30], "defaultVal": 0}, "expected": 20},\n  "test_2": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [], "acceptedVals": [], "defaultVal": 42}, "expected": 42},\n  "test_3": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [5], "acceptedVals": [-7], "defaultVal": 100}, "expected": -7},\n  "test_4": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [4, 4, 4], "acceptedVals": [11, 22, 33], "defaultVal": 0}, "expected": 11},\n  "test_5": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [1, 9, 9, 2], "acceptedVals": [5, 6, 7, 8], "defaultVal": 0}, "expected": 6},\n  "test_6": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [10, 2, 3], "acceptedVals": [99, 1, 2], "defaultVal": 0}, "expected": 99},\n  "test_7": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [1, 2, 10], "acceptedVals": [1, 2, 99], "defaultVal": 0}, "expected": 99},\n  "test_8": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [0], "acceptedVals": [55], "defaultVal": 7}, "expected": 55},\n  "test_9": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [1000000, 999999], "acceptedVals": [-1, -2], "defaultVal": 0}, "expected": -1},\n  "test_10": {"input": {"acceptedNums": [2, 8, 3, 8, 1], "acceptedVals": [4, 50, 6, 60, 7], "defaultVal": -5}, "expected": 50}\n}\n\n\nThe previous candidate was invalid:\n\n```lean\nimport Velvet.Std\nimport Extensions.Tactics\nimport Extensions.SpecDSL\nimport Extensions.VelvetPBT\nimport Mathlib.Tactic\n\nset_option maxHeartbeats 10000000\nset_option pp.coercions false\nset_option pp.funBinderTypes true\nset_option loom.semantics.termination "total"\nset_option loom.semantics.choice "demonic"\n\n/- Problem Description\n\nPaxos proposer Phase 2a value-selection rule (single pure method).\n\nScope: This specification covers exactly one core, self-contained rule of\nPaxos: the proposer\'s value-selection rule used in Phase 2a. All other Paxos\ncomponents — acceptor promise logic (Phase 1b), acceptor accept logic\n(Phase 2b), learner quorum/chosen-value detection, proposal-number\ngeneration, networking, persistence, timeouts, and leader election — are\nexplicitly out of scope and are planned as separate single-method\nspecification runs (acceptorPromise, acceptorAccept, nextProposalNumber,\nisQuorum, learnerChosenValue).\n\nPurpose: After a proposer receives promise responses from a quorum of\nacceptors, Paxos requires it to propose the value associated with the\nhighest-numbered previously accepted proposal among those responses; only if\nno acceptor in the quorum has previously accepted any value may the proposer\nuse its own value.\n\nInputs:\n- acceptedNums : Array Nat — proposal numbers of previously accepted\n  proposals reported in the promise responses. Each entry corresponds\n  positionally to the entry at the same index in acceptedVals. Only responses\n  that actually reported a previously accepted proposal are included;\n  responses reporting "nothing accepted yet" must be filtered out by the\n  caller before invoking this method.\n- acceptedVals : Array Int — the values of those previously accepted\n  proposals, positionally aligned with acceptedNums.\n- defaultVal : Int — the proposer\'s own desired value, used only when no\n  acceptor reported a previously accepted proposal.\n\nOutput:\n- result : Int — the value the proposer must propose in Phase 2a.\n\nPreconditions (explicit):\n- acceptedNums.size = acceptedVals.size. Behavior is unspecified if the\n  lengths differ; callers must guarantee equal lengths.\n- Proposal numbers are natural numbers (Nat); there is no upper bound.\n\nBehavior:\n- If both arrays are empty (no acceptor reported a prior acceptance), the\n  result is defaultVal.\n- Otherwise, the result is acceptedVals[i] where i is an index at which\n  acceptedNums attains its maximum value.\n- Tie-breaking (recorded assumption a reviewer may change): in standard\n  Paxos, distinct acceptors reporting the same proposal number must have\n  accepted the same value (a protocol invariant), so ties are semantically\n  harmless. For determinism at the specification level, if the maximum\n  proposal number occurs at multiple indices, the value at the FIRST (lowest)\n  such index is returned.\n\nBoundaries:\n- The maximum is inclusive; an array of size 1 trivially selects its only\n  value.\n- Proposal number 0 is a legal accepted proposal number (recorded\n  assumption: the caller does not reserve 0 as a sentinel; reviewer may\n  change this).\n\nMutation and ordering: The method does not mutate its inputs. Input ordering\nmatters only for the first-occurrence tie-break; otherwise the result is\norder-insensitive.\n\nDeterminism: Fully deterministic — identical inputs always produce identical\noutput.\n\nEdge and degenerate cases:\n- Empty inputs: returns defaultVal.\n- Single element: returns that element\'s value regardless of defaultVal.\n- All proposal numbers equal: returns the value at index 0.\n- defaultVal is ignored whenever the arrays are non-empty, even if\n  defaultVal is "better" by any measure.\n\nComplexity requirement (for the implementation): O(n) time in the length of\nthe arrays, O(1) additional space.\n\nWorked examples:\n- acceptedNums = [3, 7, 5], acceptedVals = [10, 20, 30], defaultVal = 0:\n  the maximum proposal number is 7 at index 1, so the result is 20.\n- acceptedNums = [], acceptedVals = [], defaultVal = 42: no prior\n  acceptances exist, so the result is 42.\n-/\n\nsection Specs\n\n-- i is the first (lowest) index at which nums attains its maximum value:\n-- i is in bounds, every entry is ≤ nums[i], and every earlier entry is\n-- strictly smaller (so i is the first occurrence of the maximum).\ndef isFirstMaxIndex (nums : Array Nat) (i : Nat) : Prop :=\n  i < nums.size ∧\n  (∀ j : Nat, j < nums.size → nums[j]! ≤ nums[i]!) ∧\n  (∀ j : Nat, j < i → nums[j]! < nums[i]!)\n\ndef precondition (acceptedNums : Array Nat) (acceptedVals : Array Int)\n    (defaultVal : Int) : Prop :=\n  acceptedNums.size = acceptedVals.size\n\ndef postcondition (acceptedNums : Array Nat) (acceptedVals : Array Int)\n    (defaultVal : Int) (result : Int) : Prop :=\n  -- Empty case: no prior acceptance reported, result is defaultVal.\n  (acceptedNums.size = 0 → result = defaultVal) ∧\n  -- Non-empty case: result is the value at the first index attaining the\n  -- maximum proposal number (this index is unique, so result is fully\n  -- determined).\n  (acceptedNums.size ≠ 0 →\n    ∃ i : Nat, isFirstMaxIndex acceptedNums i ∧ result = acceptedVals[i]!)\n\nend Specs\n\nsection Impl\n\nmethod chooseProposalValue (acceptedNums : Array Nat) (acceptedVals : Array Int)\n    (defaultVal : Int) return (result : Int)\n  require precondition acceptedNums acceptedVals defaultVal\n  ensures postcondition acceptedNums acceptedVals defaultVal result\ndo\n  return defaultVal\n\nprove_correct chooseProposalValue by sorry\n\nend Impl\n\nsection TestCases\n\n-- Test 1: worked example; maximum 7 at index 1.\ndef test1_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[3, 7, 5]\ndef test1_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[10, 20, 30]\ndef test1_defaultVal : Int := 0\ndef test1_Expected : Int := 20\n\n-- Test 2: empty inputs; returns defaultVal.\ndef test2_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[]\ndef test2_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[]\ndef test2_defaultVal : Int := 42\ndef test2_Expected : Int := 42\n\n-- Test 3: single element; returns its value regardless of defaultVal.\ndef test3_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[5]\ndef test3_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[-7]\ndef test3_defaultVal : Int := 100\ndef test3_Expected : Int := -7\n\n-- Test 4: all proposal numbers equal; first-index tie-break returns index 0.\ndef test4_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[4, 4, 4]\ndef test4_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[11, 22, 33]\ndef test4_defaultVal : Int := 0\ndef test4_Expected : Int := 11\n\n-- Test 5: maximum 9 occurs at indices 1 and 2; first occurrence wins.\ndef test5_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[1, 9, 9, 2]\ndef test5_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[5, 6, 7, 8]\ndef test5_defaultVal : Int := 0\ndef test5_Expected : Int := 6\n\n-- Test 6: maximum at the first index.\ndef test6_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[10, 2, 3]\ndef test6_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[99, 1, 2]\ndef test6_defaultVal : Int := 0\ndef test6_Expected : Int := 99\n\n-- Test 7: maximum at the last index.\ndef test7_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[1, 2, 10]\ndef test7_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[1, 2, 99]\ndef test7_defaultVal : Int := 0\ndef test7_Expected : Int := 99\n\n-- Test 8: proposal number 0 is a legal accepted proposal number.\ndef test8_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[0]\ndef test8_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[55]\ndef test8_defaultVal : Int := 7\ndef test8_Expected : Int := 55\n\n-- Test 9: large proposal numbers; negative values are legal.\ndef test9_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[1000000, 999999]\ndef test9_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[-1, -2]\ndef test9_defaultVal : Int := 0\ndef test9_Expected : Int := -1\n\n-- Test 10: maximum 8 occurs at indices 1 and 3; first occurrence wins;\n-- defaultVal ignored for non-empty arrays.\ndef test10_acceptedNums : Array Nat := #[2, 8, 3, 8, 1]\ndef test10_acceptedVals : Array Int := #[4, 50, 6, 60, 7]\ndef test10_defaultVal : Int := -5\ndef test10_Expected : Int := 50\n\nend TestCases\n\n```\n\nValidation or build feedback:\n\n\nCorrect every reported issue without changing the reviewed requirements.\n\nReturn only the complete Lean file.', 'role': 'user'}], 'model': 'anthropic-claude-fable-5', 'max_completion_tokens': 8192,